                <note rend="inline" type="source">816.01/36: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Costa Rica</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Werlich</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San José</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-12-24T11:00:00-06:00"
                            >December 24, 1931—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 5:05 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>62. Referring to Department’s telegram No. 42, December 20, 1 p.m., the Minister
                    for Foreign Affairs has just informed me of the decision taken last night by the
                    Costa Rican Government sitting with the President of the Republic not to
                    recognize present regime in Salvador, and that Costa Rican diplomatic
                    representatives at San Salvador, Guatemala City and at Washington informed by
                    telegraph thereof this morning. Decision based on obligations of Costa Rica
                    through 1923 treaty. Statement by the Foreign Minister to the press makes no
                    mention of the United States but cites cooperation of Costa Rica with Guatemala
                    and Honduras in the matter.</p>
                <p>Above text telegraphed to the Legation at San Salvador.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Werlich</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
